owspan=2 {{Won}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=1269 |title=Scream Award Nominees Announced |website=Shocktillyoudrop.com |access-date=2007-09-05 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fest08.sffs.org/awards/midnight_08.php |title=MIDNIGHT AWARDS |website=Fest08.sffs.org |date= |access-date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231072214/http://fest08.sffs.org/awards/midnight_08.php |archive-date=2010-12-31 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n| Rose McGowan\n| [[San Francisco International Film Festival]]\n| Midnight Outstanding Achievement Award\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Dawn''\n| Sundance Film Festival\n| Short Film Grand Jury Prize\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| {{N/a}}\n| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists|Alliance of Women Film Journalists Awards]]\n| Outstanding Achievement by a Woman in the Film Industry\n| {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q211040|c=category:Rose McGowan|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n* {{IMDb name|0000535}}\n* [http://www.maximonline.com/articles/index.aspx?a_id=282&src=GM7070:MD Maxim interview]\n* [http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_11600.html MoviesOnline Interview, ''Grindhouse'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGowan, Rose}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Seattle]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American video game actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Eugene, Oregon]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Non-binary actors]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n", "name_user": "LilSlave", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePersonal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rose_McGowan"}
{"title_page": "Infanta Francisca Josefa of Portugal", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Francisca Josefa\n| image          = Infanta D. Francisca Josefa filha do Rei D. Pedro II e irm\u00e3 do Rei D. Jo\u00e3o V.jpg\n| house          = [[House of Braganza]]\n| father         = [[Pedro II of Portugal]]\n| mother         = [[Maria Sophia of Neuburg]]\n| birth_date     = 30 January 1699\n| birth_place    = [[Lisbon]], [[Kingdom of Portugal]]\n| death_date     = {{d-da|15 July 1736|30 January 1699}}\n| death_place    = Lisbon, Kingdom of Portugal\n| burial_place = [[Royal Pantheon of the Braganza Dynasty]]\n}}\n\n'''Infanta Francisca Josefa Maria Xaviera'''<ref name=women>{{cite web|title=Francisca Josefa of Portugal de Bragan\u00e7a|url=http://macgregor-sadolin.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I24200&tree=tree1|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070825/http://macgregor-sadolin.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I24200&tree=tree1|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref>({{IPA-pt|f\u027e\u0250\u0303\u02c8si\u0283k\u0250 \u0292u\u02c8z\u025bf\u0250}}; {{Lang-en|Frances Josepha}}) (30 January 1699 &ndash; 15 July 1736) was a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[infanta]]'' (princess) and the last of eight children of [[List of Portuguese monarchs|King]] [[Peter II of Portugal|Peter II]] of [[Portugal]] and his second wife [[Marie Sophie of Neuburg]].\n\nFrancisca Josefa was born and died in [[Lisbon]]. [[Charles Emmanuel III of Sardinia]] was proposed as a possible marriage for the infanta in 1720-21, but nothing came of it. She  never married nor had issue and she died when she was 37 years old. She is buried at the [[Royal Pantheon of the Braganza Dynasty]].\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Francisca Josefa of Braganza'''\n|2= 2. [[Peter II of Portugal]]\n|3= 3. [[Maria Sophia of Neuburg]]\n|4= 4. [[John IV of Portugal]]\n|5= 5. [[Luisa de Guzm\u00e1n]]\n|6= 6. [[Philip William, Elector Palatine]]\n|7= 7. [[Elisabeth Amalie of Hesse-Darmstadt]]\n|8= 8. [[Teod\u00f3sio II, Duke of Braganza]]\n|9= 9. [[Ana de Velasco y Gir\u00f3n]]\n|10= 10. [[Manuel P\u00e9rez de Guzm\u00e1n y Silva, 8th Duke of Medina Sidonia|Manuel de Guzm\u00e1n y Silva, Duke of Medina Sidonia]]\n|11= 11. [[Juana G\u00f3mez de Sandoval y de la Cerda|Juana de Sandoval y de la Cerda]]\n|12= 12. [[Wolfgang William, Count Palatine of Neuburg]]\n|13= 13. [[Magdalene of Bavaria]]\n|14= 14. [[George II, Landgrave of Hesse-Darmstadt]]\n|15= 15. [[Sophia Eleonore of Saxony]]\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal |last=Raggi |first=Giuseppina |title=The Lost Opportunity: Two Projects of Filippo Juvarra Concerning Royal Theaters and the Marriage Policy between the Courts of Turin and Lisbon (1719-1722) |journal=Music in Art: International Journal for Music Iconography |volume=44 |issue=1\u20132 |date=2019 |pages=119\u2013137 |issn=1522-7464 }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{House of Braganza}}\n{{Portuguese infantas}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francisca Josefa, Infanta Of Portugal}}\n[[Category:Portuguese infantas]]\n[[Category:Portuguese royalty]]\n[[Category:People from Lisbon]]\n[[Category:1699 births]]\n[[Category:1736 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Monastery of S\u00e3o Vicente de Fora]]\n[[Category:House of Braganza]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese women]]\n[[Category:18th-century Portuguese women]]\n\n\n{{Portugal-royal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name           = Francisca Josefa\n| image          = Infanta D. Francisca Josefa filha do Rei D. Pedro II e irm\u00e3 do Rei D. Jo\u00e3o V.jpg\n| house          = [[House of Braganza]]\n| father         = [[Pedro II of Portugal]]\n| mother         = [[Maria Sophia of Neuburg]]\n| birth_date     = 30 January 1699\n| birth_place    = [[Lisbon]], [[Kingdom of Portugal]]\n| death_date     = {{d-da|15 July 1736|30 January 1699}}\n| death_place    = Lisbon, Kingdom of Portugal\n| burial_place = [[Royal Pantheon of the Braganza Dynasty]]\n}}\n\n'''Infanta Francisca Josefa Maria Xaviera'''<ref name=women>{{cite web|title=Francisca Josefa of Portugal de Bragan\u00e7a|url=http://macgregor-sadolin.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I24200&tree=tree1|accessdate=19 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407070825/http://macgregor-sadolin.com/genealogy/getperson.php?personID=I24200&tree=tree1|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref>({{IPA-pt|f\u027e\u0250\u0303\u02c8si\u0283k\u0250 \u0292u\u02c8z\u025bf\u0250}}; {{Lang-en|Frances Josepha}}) (30 January 1699 &ndash; 15 July 1736) was a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] ''[[infanta]]'' (princess) and the last of eight children of [[List of Portuguese monarchs|King]] [[Peter II of Portugal|Peter II]] of [[Portugal]] and his second wife [[Marie Sophie of Neuburg]].\n\nFrancisca Josefa was born and died in [[Lisbon]]. [[Charles Emmanuel III of Sardinia]] was proposed as a possible marriage for the infanta in 1720-21, but nothing came of it. She  never married nor had issue and she died when she was 37 years old. She is buried at the [[Royal Pantheon of the Braganza Dynasty]].\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Francisca Josefa of Braganza'''\n|2= 2. [[Peter II of Portugal]]\n|3= 3. [[Maria Sophia of Neuburg]]\n|4= 4. [[John IV of Portugal]]\n|5= 5. [[Luisa de Guzm\u00e1n]]\n|6= 6. [[Philip William, Elector Palatine]]\n|7= 7. [[Elisabeth Amalie of Hesse-Darmstadt]]\n|8= 8. [[Teod\u00f3sio II, Duke of Braganza]]\n|9= 9. [[Ana de Velasco y Gir\u00f3n]]\n|10= 10. [[Manuel P\u00e9rez de Guzm\u00e1n y Silva, 8th Duke of Medina Sidonia|Manuel de Guzm\u00e1n y Silva, 8th Duke of Medina Sidonia]]\n|11= 11. [[Juana G\u00f3mez de Sandoval y de la Cerda|Juana de Sandoval y de la Cerda]]\n|12= 12. [[Wolfgang William, Count Palatine of Neuburg]]\n|13= 13. [[Magdalene of Bavaria]]\n|14= 14. [[George II, Landgrave of Hesse-Darmstadt]]\n|15= 15. [[Sophia Eleonore of Saxony]]\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite journal |last=Raggi |first=Giuseppina |title=The Lost Opportunity: Two Projects of Filippo Juvarra Concerning Royal Theaters and the Marriage Policy between the Courts of Turin and Lisbon (1719-1722) |journal=Music in Art: International Journal for Music Iconography |volume=44 |issue=1\u20132 |date=2019 |pages=119\u2013137 |issn=1522-7464 }}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{House of Braganza}}\n{{Portuguese infantas}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Francisca Josefa, Infanta Of Portugal}}\n[[Category:Portuguese infantas]]\n[[Category:Portuguese royalty]]\n[[Category:People from Lisbon]]\n[[Category:1699 births]]\n[[Category:1736 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials at the Monastery of S\u00e3o Vicente de Fora]]\n[[Category:House of Braganza]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:18th-century Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Portuguese women]]\n[[Category:18th-century Portuguese women]]\n\n\n{{Portugal-royal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "M. Armando", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAncestry", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infanta_Francisca_Josefa_of_Portugal"}
{"title_page": "Cory Branan", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Cory Branan\n| image = Cory Branan DC 1.jpg\n| caption = Cory Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington,&nbsp;DC) October&nbsp;2015\n| alt = Cory Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington, DC) October 2015\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Cory D. Branan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|12|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| origin = [[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]], [[Mississippi]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| genre = [[Alternative country]]<br/>[[Rock music|Rock]]<br/>[[Folk music|Folk]]\n| occupation = \n| instrument = [[Lead singer|Vocals]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| years_active = 2000\u2013present\n| label = [[Bloodshot Records]]<br/>Madjack\n| associated_acts = [[Lucero (band)|Lucero]]<br/>[[Thrift Store Cowboys]]<br/>[[Jason Isbell]]\n| website = {{URL|corybranan.com}}\n}}\n[[File:Cory Branan Whitewater Tavern.jpg|thumb|Branan at The Whitewater Tavern (Little Rock, AR) New Year's Eve 2010]]\n[[File:Cory Branan Brooklyn.jpg|thumb|Branan at Rough Trade (Brooklyn,&nbsp;NY) February 2016]]\n[[File:Cory Branan DC 2.jpg|thumb|Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington,&nbsp;DC) October&nbsp;2015]]\n'''Cory Branan''' (born December 15, 1974) is an [[United States|American]] [[singer-songwriter]] from [[Mississippi]].<ref name=NPR-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Block|first1=Melissa|title=Cory Branan: A 'No-Hit Wonder,' Making Small-Batch Country Music|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/27/343432306/cory-branan-a-no-hit-wonder-making-small-batch-country-music|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=Vice-Noisey-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Knox|first1=Ron|title=Noisey - Cory Branan: A True No-Hit Wonder|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/cory-branan-a-true-no-hit-wonder|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBranan was born in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Calvin|title=Ep#216 Cory Branan writes second-helping songs|url=https://americanamusicshow.com/ep216-cory-branan-writes-second-helping-songs/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Americana Music Show|date=20 October 2014|format=Podcast|quote=Interview at 36.08}}</ref> to parents Dallas Lee Branan, a jet mechanic at [[FedEx]], and Peggy Branan (n\u00e9e Rhodes).<ref name=DesotoTimes-DallasLeeBranan-Obit-2010>{{cite news|title=Dallas Lee Branan|url=http://www.desototimes.com/obituaries/dallas-lee-branan/article_c62e8afe-aeb4-58a4-bcd8-40448aa39bb6.html|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=DeSoto Times-Tribune|date=24 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=TateRecord-DallasLeeBranan-2010>{{cite news|title=Tate Record, Obituaries 3-2-10: Dallas Lee Branan|url=http://www.taterecord.com/contentitem/359551/2368/obituaries-3210|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Tate Democrat-Record|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> He grew up in [[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]], [[Mississippi]], in the northwest corner of [[Mississippi]], the third largest city in Mississippi and a suburb of [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Danton|first1=Eric R.|title=Cory Branan Explores \u2018Tangled Roots\u2019 on \u2018The No-Hit Wonder\u2019 (Album Premiere)|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/08/12/cory-branan-explores-tangled-roots-on-the-no-hit-wonder-album-premiere/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=12 August 2014}}</ref> His family comes from [[Arkabutla, Mississippi|Arkabutla]], [[Mississippi]]. He grew up with musical influences from church, gospel music his dad listened to, and his family: his father played the drums, his grandfather played guitar and his great-grandfather played the violin.<ref name=Click-NoHitWonder-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hilder|first1=Casey|title=No-Hit Wonder|url=http://www.myclickmag.com/#!042016-no-hit-wonder/c1ixy|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Click Magazine|date=April 2016}}</ref><ref name=SouthernLiving-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hayes|first1=Hannah|title=The Daily South: If You Haven\u2019t Heard Cory Branan\u2019s \"The No-Hit Wonder,\" You\u2019re Missing Out|url=http://thedailysouth.southernliving.com/2014/08/27/if-you-havent-heard-cory-branans-the-no-hit-wonder-youre-missing-out/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Southern Living]]|date=27 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914120016/http://thedailysouth.southernliving.com/2014/08/27/if-you-havent-heard-cory-branans-the-no-hit-wonder-youre-missing-out/|archive-date=14 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBranan learned how to play the guitar young, and by his teens, Branan was playing guitar in diverse genres from hard rock, black metal (Black Like Me), to heavy metal in local bands, eventually fronting a [[Black Sabbath]] cover band as well as playing country music.<ref name=WorldCafe-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Dye|first1=David|title=World Cafe Next: Cory Branan|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/world-cafe/2014/09/08/346096248/world-cafe-next-cory-branan|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[World Cafe]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=8 September 2014}}</ref> He credits a creative writing teacher in high school, Evelyn Simms, for suggesting books outside the usual high school curriculum and encouraging his writing.<ref name=ChicagoSunTimes-Feature-2016>{{cite news|last1=Houlihan|first1=Mary|title=Punk, metal, rap help shape Cory Branan's country music|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/punk-metal-rap-help-shape-cory-branans-country-music/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nBranan attended [[Delta State University]] in [[Cleveland, Mississippi|Cleveland]], [[Mississippi]], community college, as well as [[University of Memphis]] <ref name=\"Weld-NoHitWonder-2014\">{{cite news|last1=Ells|first1=Blake|title=The no-hit wonder|url=http://weldbham.com/blog/2014/09/23/the-no-hit-wonder-cory-branan-bottletree/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Weld for Birmingham|date=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter high school Branan moved to [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], where, among other jobs, he worked as a bartender at the [[Peabody Hotel]].<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\nIn his early 20s he began to explore the music of singer-songwriter [[John Prine]], which led to Branan writing his own songs, which he began performing at open mic nights at Memphis' Daily Planet.<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\n=== ''The Hell You Say'' ===\nAlthough initially self-released in 2001, Branan re-released his debut full-length album, ''The Hell You Say,'' on MADJACK Records on October 8, 2002. The rejuvenated album replaced three songs from the original issue with newbies \"Skateland South\" and \"American Dream\", in an effort to streamline the concept of the album.<ref name=Billboard-HellYouSay-2002>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Chris|title=Declarations of Independents. Flag Waving: Cory Branan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=branan+Declaration+of+Independents&source=bl&ots=nr7t0m_Wo1&sig=N2LQUpKXn4OAiHhf3uArSVzsTNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG7NSvsPTOAhUCGR4KHSYWBBkQ6AEIOTAE#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=28 September 2002|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Paste-HellYouSay-2003>{{cite web|last1=Aued|first1=Blake|title=Cory Branan: The Hell You Say|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2003/01/cory-branan-the-hell-you-say.html|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=1 January 2003}}</ref> Branan produced the record with Kevin Cubbins, guitarist of the band Pawtuckets, who also contributed to the record. It was recorded in Memphis at Memphis Soundworks and Humongous Studios. [[Lucero (band)|Lucero]] and the River Bluff Clan also appear.<ref name=MemphisFlyer-NARASAward-2001>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Out Of the Shadows: Cory Branan emerges with the year's best local record|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/out-of-the-shadows/Content?oid=1105385|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=18 May 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Branan made his TV network debut playing the song, \"Miss Ferguson\" on ''[[The David Letterman Show]].''<ref name=Letterman-MissFerguson-2003>{{cite web|title=Cory Branan: \"Miss Ferguson\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UqNjwkNE3wU|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[The David Letterman Show]]|date=2003}}</ref>\n\n=== ''12 Songs'' ===\nIn 2006, Branan released his sophomore effort, ''12 Songs'' on March 21, 2006, on MADJACK Records. Almost all of ''12 Songs'' were written around the same time as his debut full-length, but were saved for record number two.<ref name=ASCAP-WordsWorth12Songs-2007>{{cite news|last1=Rosenfeld|first1=Steven|title=Cory Branan - Words' Worth: With a Southerner's gift for storytelling, Cory Branan shines on 12 Songs|url=http://www.ascap.com/playback/2007/spring/radar/cory_branan.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=1 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe title of the album comes from Branan's concept for the record as more of a collection of 12 songs rather than a cohesive album.<ref name=Punknews-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Chuck|title=Cory Branan - Mutt|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/11290/cory-branan-mutt|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=Punknews.org|date=26 June 2012}}</ref> Jody Steven from [[Big Star (band)|Big Star]] played drums on the record.<ref name=ASCAP-WordsWorth12Songs-2007 /> \"Sweet Janine\" is a song loosely based on and inspired by the death of his best friend in elementary school who drowned from an asthma attack at a pool party.<ref name=ASCAP-12Songs-2007>{{cite news|title=ASCAP Audio Portrait: Cory Branan|url=http://www.ascap.com/audioportraits/b/cory_branan.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=16 April 2007|format=Audio clips}}</ref> Branan said that he wrote both of his first two records while sitting in the bustling food court of the Oak Court Mall in Memphis.<ref name=SongwritersOnProcess-2015>{{cite news|title=Cory Branan|url=http://www.songwritersonprocess.com/blog/2015/1/26/cory-branan|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Songwriters On Process|date=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mutt'' ===\nIn 2011, Branan signed with [[Bloodshot Records]]. Six years after his prior record,<ref name=MemphisFlyer-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Turning the Corner|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/turning-the-corner/Content?oid=3228015|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> he released ''Mutt'' on May 22, 2012.<ref name=MemphisFlyer-Bloodshot-2012>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Cory Branan Signs with Bloodshot Records; Mutt Due in Spring|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/SingAllKinds/archives/2012/01/18/cory-branan-signs-with-bloodshot-records-mutt-due-in-spring|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=18 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[American Songwriter]]'' praised his \"hushed, dry whiskey voice and his sharp edged, story song lyrics [which] make the appropriately titled Mutt a mongrel that rewards repeated spins with an understanding of Branan\u2019s many influences and an appreciation for his largely impressionistic, thought-provoking words.\"<ref name=AmericanSongwriter-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Horowitz|first1=Hal|title=Cory Brannan: Mutt|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/06/cory-brannan-mutt/|accessdate=5 June 2012|work=[[American Songwriter]]|date=4 June 2012}}</ref> The title ''Mutt'' actually comes from his most frequent answer when asked to describe his own music. Originally intended to be titled ''Midtown'' - in reference to the diverse neighborhood in Memphis - Branan said that the theme of each song on the record reminds him of the poem ''[[The Oven Bird]]'' by [[Robert Frost]] \"which paints a picture of the fallen petals of post-spring flowers to convey fleeting beauty and ends with the question, 'What to make of a diminished thing.'\"<ref name=MountainSouth-Mutt-2008>{{cite news|last1=Paik|first1=Ernest|title=Cory Branan|work=Mountain South|date=2008}}</ref> The record received positive reviews.<ref name=CMTNews-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Parton|first1=Chris|title=Cory Branan Unleashes New Album, Mutt|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1687450/cory-branan-unleashes-new-album-mutt.jhtml|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|date=14 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=Paste-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Deusner|first1=Stephen M.|title=Cory Branan: Mutt|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/05/cory-branan-mutt.html|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe album was also notable for its album cover. The photograph by Joshua Black Wilkins features a topless woman wearing a painted [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]] mask Branan created, which Branan said he dreamed, that she represents a muse.<ref name=ConnectSavannah-Mutt-2013>{{cite news|last1=DeYoung|first1=Bill|title=Conversations with musical 'Mutt' Cory Branan|url=http://www.connectsavannah.com/savannah/conversations-with-musical-mutt-cory-branan/Content?oid=2178173|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Connect Savannah|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> In discussing the cover, Branan described her being like a \"Mississippi Madonna with a boom box, kind of like a folk art thing.\"<ref name=CMTNews-Mutt-2012 />\n\n=== ''The No-Hit Wonder'' ===\n[[File:Cory Branan 2015.jpg|thumb|Branan performing in 2015]]\nIn 2014, Branan released ''The No-Hit Wonder'' on [[Bloodshot Records]] on August 19, 2014.<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /> The album, produced by Paul Ebersold and recorded over the period of three days in Nashville at The Sound Kitchen,<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /><ref name=MemphisFlyer-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Reager|first1=J. D.|title=Cory Branan at 1884 Saturday|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/cory-branan-at-1884-saturday/Content?oid=3774664|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=6 November 2014}}</ref> features contributions by [[Craig Finn]] and [[Steve Selvidge]] of [[The Hold Steady]], [[Tim Easton]], [[Caitlin Rose]], [[Austin Lucas]], and [[Jason Isbell]].<ref name=PopMatters-NoHitWonder-Aug-2014>{{cite web|last=Recker|first=Scott|title=Cory Branan: The No-Hit Wonder|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/184545-cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder/|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=20 August 2014}}</ref>  \"Slick\" Joe Fick from The Dempseys plays upright bass on the song \"Sour Mash\" \u2013 a song about a dry county where a whiskey company makes its liquor \u2013 and [[Audley Freed]] also appears. Sadler Vaden ([[Drivin N Cryin]], [[Jason Isbell]]) is on electric guitar and John Radford on play drums on the record.<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\nThe record was listed by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine as one of the top 40 country records of 2014.<ref name=RollingStone-40BestCountryAlbums-2014>{{cite news|last1=Keiper|first1=Nicole|title=40 Best Country Albums of 2014|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/40-best-country-albums-of-2014-20141210/cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder-20141209|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 December 2014}}</ref> Branan said that the passing of family members as well as his growing family changed his approach to songwriting. \"You Make Me,\" which Isbell sings on, is a song about his wife, and \"All I Got And Gone\" is about the passing of his father.<ref name=ASCAP-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|title=ASCAP Audio Portrait: Cory Branan's The No Hit Wonder|url=http://www.ascap.com/audioportraits/b/cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=16 July 2014|format=Audio clips}}</ref> Drummer John Radford (the Dynamites) and pedal steel guitar player [[Robby Turner]] play on the track \"No Hit Wonder.\"<ref name=PopMatters-NoHitWonder-Oct-2014>{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Jennifer|title=Subverting the Rules: An Interview with Cory Branan|url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/187131-subverting-the-rules-an-interview-with-cory-branan/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Adios'' ===\nBranan released his fifth album, Adios, on April 7, 2017. Advertised as \"Cory Branan\u2019s death record\", the record features Robbie Crowell of [[Deer Tick (band)|Deer Tick]] on drums and percussion, keys, and horns; and James Haggerty on bass. Guest musicians include [[Amanda Shires]] on fiddle and vocals, plus backing vocals on ''I Only Know'' by [[Laura Jane Grace]] and [[Dave Hause]].<ref name=Adios-Bloodshot-Records>{{cite press release|last=Bloodshot Records|title=Adios - Bloodshot Records|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/album/adios|accessdate=12 December 2019|work=[[Bloodshot Records]]}}</ref>\n\n''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' described the album as \"possibly his best album to date \u2014 it\u2019s certainly his most musically imaginative and arguably his wisest\", but also criticised its length; \"At 14 tracks, it meanders, occasionally lags, and indulges far too many tangents and jarring transitions\".<ref name=Pitchfork-Adios-Review>{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Deusner|title=40 Best Country and Americana Albums of 2017|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/23091-adios/|accessdate=12 December 2019|publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 April 2017}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' listed it as the 27th Best Country and Americana Album of 2017.<ref name=Rolling-Stone-Best-2017>{{cite web|first=Kip|last=Moore|title=Cory Branan: Adios review|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country-lists/40-best-country-and-americana-albums-of-2017-204874/cory-branan-adios-196276/|accessdate=12 December 2019|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nIn 2000, the Memphis chapter of [[The Recording Academy]] (formerly known as the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences (NARAS)) gave Branan the Phillips Award for Newcomer of the Year. At that time he didn\u2019t even have a recording contract yet.<ref name=Billboard-HellYouSay-2002 /><ref name=MemphisFlyer-NARASAward-2001 />\n\nIn the fall of 2014, Branan was listed in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of 10 New Artists You Need to Know.<ref name=RollingStone-10ArtistsToKnow-2014>{{cite news|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=10 Country Artists You Need to Know Now|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/new-country-artists-2014-20141010/cory-branan-20141010|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Collaborations ==\nIn April 2015, Branan was part of a [[Record Store Day]] release with label-mate, [[Lydia Loveless]]. The two artists cover two [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] songs: Loveless doing ''[[I Would Die 4 U]]'' and Branan doing ''[[Parade (Prince album)|Under The Cherry Moon]].'' The 7\" limited edition releases was pressed onto purple vinyl.<ref name=RollingStone-PrinceSplit-2016>{{cite news|last1=Parton|first1=Chris|title=Hear Lydia Loveless Cover Prince's 'I Would Die 4 U'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-lydia-loveless-reverent-cover-of-princes-i-would-die-4-u-20160421|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBranan lives in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=MotherChurchPew-Nashville-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hubbard|first1=Susan|title=Interview with: Cory Branan|url=http://www.motherchurchpew.com/2016/08/03/interview-with-cory-branan/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Mother Church Pew|date=3 August 2016}}</ref> with his wife and son.<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /> Branan and his wife were married at the Shack Up Inn in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi|Clarksdale]], [[Mississippi]].<ref name=RollingStone-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Hear Cory Branan & Jason Isbell's 'You Make Me'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/cory-branan-recruits-jason-isbell-for-you-make-me-song-premiere-20140701|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 July 2014}}</ref> Branan also has a daughter from a previous relationship who lives in [[Tulsa]].<ref name=ChicagoSunTimes-Feature-2016 /><ref name=Blurt-Mutt-2014>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=John B.|title=Wonder-Ful: Cory Branan|url=http://blurtonline.com/feature/wonder-ful-cory-branan/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Blurt (magazine)|Blurt Magazine]]|date=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n;Albums\n* 2002: ''The Hell You Say'' (Madjack Records)\n* 2006: ''12 Songs'' (Madjack Records)\n* 2012: ''Mutt'' (Bloodshot Records)\n* 2014: ''The No-Hit Wonder'' (Bloodshot Records)\n* 2017: \"Adios\" (Bloodshot Records)\n;EPs\n* 2009: ''Jon Snodgrass / Cory Branan'' (Suburban Home)<ref name=SuburbanHome-Snodgrass-Split-2009>{{cite news|title=Cory Branan/Jon Snodgrass \"Split\" Cassette|url=http://suburbanhomerecords.limitedrun.com/products/4131-cory-branan-jon-snodgrass-split-cassette|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Suburban Home|date=2009}}</ref>\n;Singles\n* 2014: ''Under the Cherry Moon:'' \"[[I Would Die 4 U]]\" by [[Lydia Loveless]] / \"[[Parade (Prince album)|Under The Cherry Moon]]\" by Cory Branan (Bloodshot Records)<ref name=Bloodshot-228-RecordStoreDay-2015>{{cite news|title=BS 228: I Would Die 4 U / Under the Cherry Moon (7\" single)|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/album/i-would-die-4-u-under-cherry-moon-7-single|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Bloodshot Records]]|date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Cory Branan}}\n* [http://www.corybranan.com Cory Branan]\n* [http://www.bloodshotrecords.com/artist/cory-branan Cory Branan] at [[Bloodshot Records]]\n* [http://www.madjackrecords.com/the-artists/cory-branan/ Cory Branan] at MADJACK Records\n* {{discogs artist|1970005-Cory-Branan|Cory Branan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Branan, Cory}}\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American alternative country singers]]\n[[Category:People from Southaven, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Bloodshot Records artists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Cory Branan\n| image = Cory Branan DC 1.jpg\n| caption = Cory Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington,&nbsp;DC) October&nbsp;2015\n| alt = Cory Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington, DC) October 2015\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Cory D. Branan\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|12|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| origin = [[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]], [[Mississippi]] [[United States|U.S.]]\n| genre = [[Alternative country]]<br/>[[Rock music|Rock]]<br/>[[Folk music|Folk]]\n| occupation = \n| instrument = [[Lead singer|Vocals]]<br/>[[Guitar]]\n| years_active = 2000\u2013present\n| label = [[Bloodshot Records]]<br/>Madjack\n| associated_acts = [[Lucero (band)|Lucero]]<br/>[[Thrift Store Cowboys]]<br/>[[Jason Isbell]]\n| website = {{URL|corybranan.com}}\n}}\n[[File:Cory Branan Whitewater Tavern.jpg|thumb|Branan at The Whitewater Tavern (Little Rock, AR) New Year's Eve 2010]]\n[[File:Cory Branan Brooklyn.jpg|thumb|Branan at Rough Trade (Brooklyn,&nbsp;NY) February 2016]]\n[[File:Cory Branan DC 2.jpg|thumb|Branan at Gypsy Sally's (Washington,&nbsp;DC) October&nbsp;2015]]\n'''Cory Branan''' (born December 15, 1974) is an [[United States|American]] [[singer-songwriter]] from [[Mississippi]].<ref name=NPR-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Block|first1=Melissa|title=Cory Branan: A 'No-Hit Wonder,' Making Small-Batch Country Music|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/27/343432306/cory-branan-a-no-hit-wonder-making-small-batch-country-music|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[All Things Considered]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=Vice-Noisey-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Knox|first1=Ron|title=Noisey - Cory Branan: A True No-Hit Wonder|url=http://noisey.vice.com/blog/cory-branan-a-true-no-hit-wonder|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=27 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBranan was born in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Powers|first1=Calvin|title=Ep#216 Cory Branan writes second-helping songs|url=https://americanamusicshow.com/ep216-cory-branan-writes-second-helping-songs/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Americana Music Show|date=20 October 2014|format=Podcast|quote=Interview at 36.08}}</ref> to parents Dallas Lee Branan, a jet mechanic at [[FedEx]], and Peggy Branan (n\u00e9e Rhodes).<ref name=DesotoTimes-DallasLeeBranan-Obit-2010>{{cite news|title=Dallas Lee Branan|url=http://www.desototimes.com/obituaries/dallas-lee-branan/article_c62e8afe-aeb4-58a4-bcd8-40448aa39bb6.html|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=DeSoto Times-Tribune|date=24 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=TateRecord-DallasLeeBranan-2010>{{cite news|title=Tate Record, Obituaries 3-2-10: Dallas Lee Branan|url=http://www.taterecord.com/contentitem/359551/2368/obituaries-3210|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Tate Democrat-Record|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> He grew up in [[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]], [[Mississippi]], in the northwest corner of [[Mississippi]], the third largest city in Mississippi and a suburb of [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]].<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Danton|first1=Eric R.|title=Cory Branan Explores \u2018Tangled Roots\u2019 on \u2018The No-Hit Wonder\u2019 (Album Premiere)|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/08/12/cory-branan-explores-tangled-roots-on-the-no-hit-wonder-album-premiere/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=12 August 2014}}</ref> His family comes from [[Arkabutla, Mississippi|Arkabutla]], [[Mississippi]]. He grew up with musical influences from church, gospel music his dad listened to, and his family: his father played the drums, his grandfather played guitar and his great-grandfather played the violin.<ref name=Click-NoHitWonder-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hilder|first1=Casey|title=No-Hit Wonder|url=http://www.myclickmag.com/#!042016-no-hit-wonder/c1ixy|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Click Magazine|date=April 2016}}</ref><ref name=SouthernLiving-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hayes|first1=Hannah|title=The Daily South: If You Haven\u2019t Heard Cory Branan\u2019s \"The No-Hit Wonder,\" You\u2019re Missing Out|url=http://thedailysouth.southernliving.com/2014/08/27/if-you-havent-heard-cory-branans-the-no-hit-wonder-youre-missing-out/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Southern Living]]|date=27 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914120016/http://thedailysouth.southernliving.com/2014/08/27/if-you-havent-heard-cory-branans-the-no-hit-wonder-youre-missing-out/|archive-date=14 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBranan learned how to play the guitar young, and by his teens, Branan was playing guitar in diverse genres from hard rock, black metal (Black Like Me), to heavy metal in local bands, eventually fronting a [[Black Sabbath]] cover band as well as playing country music.<ref name=WorldCafe-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Dye|first1=David|title=World Cafe Next: Cory Branan|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/world-cafe/2014/09/08/346096248/world-cafe-next-cory-branan|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[World Cafe]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=8 September 2014}}</ref> He credits a creative writing teacher in high school, Evelyn Simms, for suggesting books outside the usual high school curriculum and encouraging his writing.<ref name=ChicagoSunTimes-Feature-2016>{{cite news|last1=Houlihan|first1=Mary|title=Punk, metal, rap help shape Cory Branan's country music|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/punk-metal-rap-help-shape-cory-branans-country-music/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nBranan attended [[Delta State University]] in [[Cleveland, Mississippi|Cleveland]], [[Mississippi]], community college, as well as [[University of Memphis]].<ref name=\"Weld-NoHitWonder-2014\">{{cite news|last1=Ells|first1=Blake|title=The no-hit wonder|url=http://weldbham.com/blog/2014/09/23/the-no-hit-wonder-cory-branan-bottletree/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Weld for Birmingham|date=23 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter high school Branan moved to [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], where, among other jobs, he worked as a bartender at the [[Peabody Hotel]].<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\nIn his early 20s he began to explore the music of singer-songwriter [[John Prine]], which led to Branan writing his own songs, which he began performing at open mic nights at Memphis' Daily Planet.<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\n=== ''The Hell You Say'' ===\nAlthough initially self-released in 2001, Branan re-released his debut full-length album, ''The Hell You Say,'' on MADJACK Records on October 8, 2002. The rejuvenated album replaced three songs from the original issue with newbies \"Skateland South\" and \"American Dream\", in an effort to streamline the concept of the album.<ref name=Billboard-HellYouSay-2002>{{cite news|last1=Morris|first1=Chris|title=Declarations of Independents. Flag Waving: Cory Branan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=branan+Declaration+of+Independents&source=bl&ots=nr7t0m_Wo1&sig=N2LQUpKXn4OAiHhf3uArSVzsTNk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG7NSvsPTOAhUCGR4KHSYWBBkQ6AEIOTAE#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=28 September 2002|language=en}}</ref><ref name=Paste-HellYouSay-2003>{{cite web|last1=Aued|first1=Blake|title=Cory Branan: The Hell You Say|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2003/01/cory-branan-the-hell-you-say.html|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=1 January 2003}}</ref> Branan produced the record with Kevin Cubbins, guitarist of the band Pawtuckets, who also contributed to the record. It was recorded in Memphis at Memphis Soundworks and Humongous Studios. [[Lucero (band)|Lucero]] and the River Bluff Clan also appear.<ref name=MemphisFlyer-NARASAward-2001>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Out Of the Shadows: Cory Branan emerges with the year's best local record|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/out-of-the-shadows/Content?oid=1105385|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=18 May 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Branan made his TV network debut playing the song, \"Miss Ferguson\" on ''[[The David Letterman Show]].''<ref name=Letterman-MissFerguson-2003>{{cite web|title=Cory Branan: \"Miss Ferguson\"|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UqNjwkNE3wU|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[The David Letterman Show]]|date=2003}}</ref>\n\n=== ''12 Songs'' ===\nIn 2006, Branan released his sophomore effort, ''12 Songs'' on March 21, 2006, on MADJACK Records. Almost all of ''12 Songs'' were written around the same time as his debut full-length, but were saved for record number two.<ref name=ASCAP-WordsWorth12Songs-2007>{{cite news|last1=Rosenfeld|first1=Steven|title=Cory Branan - Words' Worth: With a Southerner's gift for storytelling, Cory Branan shines on 12 Songs|url=http://www.ascap.com/playback/2007/spring/radar/cory_branan.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=1 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe title of the album comes from Branan's concept for the record as more of a collection of 12 songs rather than a cohesive album.<ref name=Punknews-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Cunningham|first1=Chuck|title=Cory Branan - Mutt|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/11290/cory-branan-mutt|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=Punknews.org|date=26 June 2012}}</ref> Jody Steven from [[Big Star (band)|Big Star]] played drums on the record.<ref name=ASCAP-WordsWorth12Songs-2007 /> \"Sweet Janine\" is a song loosely based on and inspired by the death of his best friend in elementary school who drowned from an asthma attack at a pool party.<ref name=ASCAP-12Songs-2007>{{cite news|title=ASCAP Audio Portrait: Cory Branan|url=http://www.ascap.com/audioportraits/b/cory_branan.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=16 April 2007|format=Audio clips}}</ref> Branan said that he wrote both of his first two records while sitting in the bustling food court of the Oak Court Mall in Memphis.<ref name=SongwritersOnProcess-2015>{{cite news|title=Cory Branan|url=http://www.songwritersonprocess.com/blog/2015/1/26/cory-branan|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Songwriters On Process|date=26 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Mutt'' ===\nIn 2011, Branan signed with [[Bloodshot Records]]. Six years after his prior record,<ref name=MemphisFlyer-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Turning the Corner|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/turning-the-corner/Content?oid=3228015|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=19 July 2012}}</ref> he released ''Mutt'' on May 22, 2012.<ref name=MemphisFlyer-Bloodshot-2012>{{cite news|last1=Herrington|first1=Chris|title=Cory Branan Signs with Bloodshot Records; Mutt Due in Spring|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/SingAllKinds/archives/2012/01/18/cory-branan-signs-with-bloodshot-records-mutt-due-in-spring|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=18 January 2012}}</ref> ''[[American Songwriter]]'' praised his \"hushed, dry whiskey voice and his sharp edged, story song lyrics [which] make the appropriately titled Mutt a mongrel that rewards repeated spins with an understanding of Branan\u2019s many influences and an appreciation for his largely impressionistic, thought-provoking words.\"<ref name=AmericanSongwriter-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Horowitz|first1=Hal|title=Cory Brannan: Mutt|url=http://www.americansongwriter.com/2012/06/cory-brannan-mutt/|accessdate=5 June 2012|work=[[American Songwriter]]|date=4 June 2012}}</ref> The title ''Mutt'' actually comes from his most frequent answer when asked to describe his own music. Originally intended to be titled ''Midtown'' - in reference to the diverse neighborhood in Memphis - Branan said that the theme of each song on the record reminds him of the poem ''[[The Oven Bird]]'' by [[Robert Frost]] \"which paints a picture of the fallen petals of post-spring flowers to convey fleeting beauty and ends with the question, 'What to make of a diminished thing.'\"<ref name=MountainSouth-Mutt-2008>{{cite news|last1=Paik|first1=Ernest|title=Cory Branan|work=Mountain South|date=2008}}</ref> The record received positive reviews.<ref name=CMTNews-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Parton|first1=Chris|title=Cory Branan Unleashes New Album, Mutt|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1687450/cory-branan-unleashes-new-album-mutt.jhtml|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT News]]|date=14 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=Paste-Mutt-2012>{{cite news|last1=Deusner|first1=Stephen M.|title=Cory Branan: Mutt|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/05/cory-branan-mutt.html|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe album was also notable for its album cover. The photograph by Joshua Black Wilkins features a topless woman wearing a painted [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]] mask Branan created, which Branan said he dreamed, that she represents a muse.<ref name=ConnectSavannah-Mutt-2013>{{cite news|last1=DeYoung|first1=Bill|title=Conversations with musical 'Mutt' Cory Branan|url=http://www.connectsavannah.com/savannah/conversations-with-musical-mutt-cory-branan/Content?oid=2178173|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Connect Savannah|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> In discussing the cover, Branan described her being like a \"Mississippi Madonna with a boom box, kind of like a folk art thing.\"<ref name=CMTNews-Mutt-2012 />\n\n=== ''The No-Hit Wonder'' ===\n[[File:Cory Branan 2015.jpg|thumb|Branan performing in 2015]]\nIn 2014, Branan released ''The No-Hit Wonder'' on [[Bloodshot Records]] on August 19, 2014.<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /> The album, produced by Paul Ebersold and recorded over the period of three days in Nashville at The Sound Kitchen,<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /><ref name=MemphisFlyer-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Reager|first1=J. D.|title=Cory Branan at 1884 Saturday|url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/cory-branan-at-1884-saturday/Content?oid=3774664|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Memphis Flyer]]|date=6 November 2014}}</ref> features contributions by [[Craig Finn]] and [[Steve Selvidge]] of [[The Hold Steady]], [[Tim Easton]], [[Caitlin Rose]], [[Austin Lucas]], and [[Jason Isbell]].<ref name=PopMatters-NoHitWonder-Aug-2014>{{cite web|last=Recker|first=Scott|title=Cory Branan: The No-Hit Wonder|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/184545-cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder/|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=20 August 2014}}</ref>  \"Slick\" Joe Fick from The Dempseys plays upright bass on the song \"Sour Mash\" \u2013 a song about a dry county where a whiskey company makes its liquor \u2013 and [[Audley Freed]] also appears. Sadler Vaden ([[Drivin N Cryin]], [[Jason Isbell]]) is on electric guitar and John Radford on play drums on the record.<ref name=AmericanaMusicShow-NoHitWonder-2014 />\n\nThe record was listed by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine as one of the top 40 country records of 2014.<ref name=RollingStone-40BestCountryAlbums-2014>{{cite news|last1=Keiper|first1=Nicole|title=40 Best Country Albums of 2014|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/40-best-country-albums-of-2014-20141210/cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder-20141209|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 December 2014}}</ref> Branan said that the passing of family members as well as his growing family changed his approach to songwriting. \"You Make Me,\" which Isbell sings on, is a song about his wife, and \"All I Got And Gone\" is about the passing of his father.<ref name=ASCAP-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|title=ASCAP Audio Portrait: Cory Branan's The No Hit Wonder|url=http://www.ascap.com/audioportraits/b/cory-branan-the-no-hit-wonder.aspx|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers|ASCAP]]|date=16 July 2014|format=Audio clips}}</ref> Drummer John Radford (the Dynamites) and pedal steel guitar player [[Robby Turner]] play on the track \"No Hit Wonder.\"<ref name=PopMatters-NoHitWonder-Oct-2014>{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Jennifer|title=Subverting the Rules: An Interview with Cory Branan|url=http://www.popmatters.com/feature/187131-subverting-the-rules-an-interview-with-cory-branan/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Adios'' ===\nBranan released his fifth album, Adios, on April 7, 2017. Advertised as \"Cory Branan\u2019s death record\", the record features Robbie Crowell of [[Deer Tick (band)|Deer Tick]] on drums and percussion, keys, and horns; and James Haggerty on bass. Guest musicians include [[Amanda Shires]] on fiddle and vocals, plus backing vocals on ''I Only Know'' by [[Laura Jane Grace]] and [[Dave Hause]].<ref name=Adios-Bloodshot-Records>{{cite press release|last=Bloodshot Records|title=Adios - Bloodshot Records|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/album/adios|accessdate=12 December 2019|work=[[Bloodshot Records]]}}</ref>\n\n''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' described the album as \"possibly his best album to date \u2014 it\u2019s certainly his most musically imaginative and arguably his wisest\", but also criticised its length; \"At 14 tracks, it meanders, occasionally lags, and indulges far too many tangents and jarring transitions\".<ref name=Pitchfork-Adios-Review>{{cite web|first=Stephen|last=Deusner|title=40 Best Country and Americana Albums of 2017|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/23091-adios/|accessdate=12 December 2019|publisher=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 April 2017}}</ref> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' listed it as the 27th Best Country and Americana Album of 2017.<ref name=Rolling-Stone-Best-2017>{{cite web|first=Kip|last=Moore|title=Cory Branan: Adios review|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country-lists/40-best-country-and-americana-albums-of-2017-204874/cory-branan-adios-196276/|accessdate=12 December 2019|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nIn 2000, the Memphis chapter of [[The Recording Academy]] (formerly known as the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences (NARAS)) gave Branan the Phillips Award for Newcomer of the Year. At that time he didn\u2019t even have a recording contract yet.<ref name=Billboard-HellYouSay-2002 /><ref name=MemphisFlyer-NARASAward-2001 />\n\nIn the fall of 2014, Branan was listed in ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's list of 10 New Artists You Need to Know.<ref name=RollingStone-10ArtistsToKnow-2014>{{cite news|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=10 Country Artists You Need to Know Now|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/new-country-artists-2014-20141010/cory-branan-20141010|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Collaborations ==\nIn April 2015, Branan was part of a [[Record Store Day]] release with label-mate, [[Lydia Loveless]]. The two artists cover two [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] songs: Loveless doing ''[[I Would Die 4 U]]'' and Branan doing ''[[Parade (Prince album)|Under The Cherry Moon]].'' The 7\" limited edition releases was pressed onto purple vinyl.<ref name=RollingStone-PrinceSplit-2016>{{cite news|last1=Parton|first1=Chris|title=Hear Lydia Loveless Cover Prince's 'I Would Die 4 U'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-lydia-loveless-reverent-cover-of-princes-i-would-die-4-u-20160421|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBranan lives in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[Tennessee]],<ref name=MotherChurchPew-Nashville-2016>{{cite news|last1=Hubbard|first1=Susan|title=Interview with: Cory Branan|url=http://www.motherchurchpew.com/2016/08/03/interview-with-cory-branan/|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=Mother Church Pew|date=3 August 2016}}</ref> with his wife and son.<ref name=WSJ-NoHitWonder-2014 /> Branan and his wife were married at the Shack Up Inn in [[Clarksdale, Mississippi|Clarksdale]], [[Mississippi]].<ref name=RollingStone-NoHitWonder-2014>{{cite news|last1=Leahey|first1=Andrew|title=Hear Cory Branan & Jason Isbell's 'You Make Me'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/cory-branan-recruits-jason-isbell-for-you-make-me-song-premiere-20140701|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=1 July 2014}}</ref> Branan also has a daughter from a previous relationship who lives in [[Tulsa]].<ref name=ChicagoSunTimes-Feature-2016 /><ref name=Blurt-Mutt-2014>{{cite news|last1=Moore|first1=John B.|title=Wonder-Ful: Cory Branan|url=http://blurtonline.com/feature/wonder-ful-cory-branan/|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=[[Blurt (magazine)|Blurt Magazine]]|date=16 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n;Albums\n* 2002: ''The Hell You Say'' (Madjack Records)\n* 2006: ''12 Songs'' (Madjack Records)\n* 2012: ''Mutt'' (Bloodshot Records)\n* 2014: ''The No-Hit Wonder'' (Bloodshot Records)\n* 2017: \"Adios\" (Bloodshot Records)\n;EPs\n* 2009: ''Jon Snodgrass / Cory Branan'' (Suburban Home)<ref name=SuburbanHome-Snodgrass-Split-2009>{{cite news|title=Cory Branan/Jon Snodgrass \"Split\" Cassette|url=http://suburbanhomerecords.limitedrun.com/products/4131-cory-branan-jon-snodgrass-split-cassette|accessdate=4 September 2016|work=Suburban Home|date=2009}}</ref>\n;Singles\n* 2014: ''Under the Cherry Moon:'' \"[[I Would Die 4 U]]\" by [[Lydia Loveless]] / \"[[Parade (Prince album)|Under The Cherry Moon]]\" by Cory Branan (Bloodshot Records)<ref name=Bloodshot-228-RecordStoreDay-2015>{{cite news|title=BS 228: I Would Die 4 U / Under the Cherry Moon (7\" single)|url=https://www.bloodshotrecords.com/album/i-would-die-4-u-under-cherry-moon-7-single|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Bloodshot Records]]|date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Cory Branan}}\n* [http://www.corybranan.com Cory Branan]\n* [http://www.bloodshotrecords.com/artist/cory-branan Cory Branan] at [[Bloodshot Records]]\n* [http://www.madjackrecords.com/the-artists/cory-branan/ Cory Branan] at MADJACK Records\n* {{discogs artist|1970005-Cory-Branan|Cory Branan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Branan, Cory}}\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American alternative country singers]]\n[[Category:People from Southaven, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Bloodshot Records artists]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "38.142.236.234", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cory_Branan"}
