>\n| source2_elevation  = {{convert|1309|ft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url={{Gnis3|1547564}} |title=Geographic Names Information System entry for Straight Fork (headwaters tributary of West Fork River) (Feature ID #1547564) |author=Geographic Names Information System |authorlink=Geographic Names Information System|accessdate=2007-03-12}}</ref>\n| source_confluence            = \n| source_confluence_location   = [[Fairmont, West Virginia|Fairmont]], [[West Virginia]]\n| source_confluence_coordinates= {{coord|39|27|53|N|80|09|10|W|display=inline}}<ref name=GNIS>{{cite web |url={{Gnis3|1209053}} |title=Geographic Names Information System entry for Monongahela River (Feature ID #1209053) |author=Geographic Names Information System |authorlink=Geographic Names Information System|accessdate=2007-03-12}}</ref>\n| source_confluence_elevation  = {{convert|863|ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=GNISwf/>\n| mouth              = [[Ohio River]]\n| mouth_location     = [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| mouth_coordinates  = {{coord|40|26|30|N|80|00|58|W|display=inline,title}}<ref name=GNIS/>\n| mouth_elevation    = {{convert|709|ft|abbr=on}}<ref name=GNIS/>\n| progression        = \n| river_system       = \n| basin_size         = {{convert|7340|sqmi|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite book| last= Gillespie |first= William H. |editor= Ken Sullivan| title= The West Virginia Encyclopedia |year= 2006 |publisher= West Virginia Humanities Council |location=Charleston, W.Va. |isbn= 0-9778498-0-5 |page= 492 |chapter=Monongahela River}}</ref>\n| tributaries_left   = [[West Fork River|West Fork]], Coal Run, [[Buffalo Creek (Monongahela River tributary)|Buffalo Creek]], Hawkinberry Run, [[Paw Paw Creek]], Pharoah Run, Parker Run, Indian Creek, Birchfield Run, Meadow Run, Broad Run, Dents Run, Scotts Run, Courtney Run, Robinson Run, Crooked Run, [[Dunkard Creek]], Whiteley Creek, Little Whiteley Creek, Pegs Run, Muddy Creek, Noel Run, [[Pumpkin Run (Monongahela River tributary)|Pumpkin Run]], Rush Run, [[Tenmile Creek (Pennsylvania)|Tenmile Creek]], Fishpot Run, Barneys Run, Twomile Run, Lilly Run, Pike Run, Wood Run, Hooders Run, Maple Creek, Pigeon Creek, Dry Run, Mingo Creek, Huston Run, Lobbs Run, [[Peters Creek (Pennsylvania)|Peters Creek]], Thompson Run, Homestead Run, West Run, [[Streets Run]], [[Becks Run]]\n| tributaries_right  = [[Tygart River]], Prickett Creek, Little Creek, Whiteday Creek, Joes Run, Toms Run, Booths Run, Cobun Creek, [[Deckers Creek]], West Run, Laurel Run, Camp Run, [[Cheat River]], [[Georges_Creek_(Monongahela_River_tributary)|Georges Creek]], Jacobs Creek, Cats Run, Browns Run, Middle Run, Antram Run, Wallace Run, Hereford Hollow, Bates Run, Meadow Run, Kelley Run, Rush Run, Dunlap Creek, [[Redstone Creek (Pennsylvania)|Redstone Creek]], Lamb Lick Run, Downers Run, Speers Run, Turkey Hollow, Beckers Run, Sunfish Run, Bunola Run, Kelly Run, Mill Run, Smiths Run, Fallen Timber Run, Wylie Run, [[Youghiogheny River]], [[Crooked Run (Monongahela River tributary)|Crooked Run]], [[Turtle Creek (Monongahela River)|Turtle Creek]], Ninemile Run\n| custom_label       = \n| custom_data        = \n| extra              = \n}}\n\nThe '''Monongahela River''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0252|\u014b|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|l|\u0259}} {{respell|m\u0259|NONG|g\u0259|HEE|l\u0259}}, {{IPAc-en|-|\u02c8|h|e\u026a|-}} {{respell|-|HAY|-}})<ref>There are several ways to pronounce this word that are acceptable. From \"Geographical Names\" of Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary, Eleventh Edition (2009):  {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0252|n|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|l|\u0259}}, {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0252|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|h|i\u02d0|l|\u0259}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02cc|n|\u0252|\u014b|\u0261|\u0259|\u02c8|h|e\u026a|l|\u0259}}.</ref> \u2014 often referred to locally as '''the Mon''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0252|n}}) \u2014 is a {{convert|130|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}}<ref name=NHD>U.S. Geological Survey. National Hydrography Dataset high-resolution flowline data. [http://viewer.nationalmap.gov/viewer/ The National Map], accessed August 15, 2011</ref> [[river]] on the [[Allegheny Plateau]] in [[North-Central West Virginia|north-central]] [[West Virginia]] and [[Western Pennsylvania|southwestern]] [[Pennsylvania]].  The river flows from the confluence of its west and east forks in north central West Virginia northeasterly into southwestern Pennsylvania, then northerly to Pittsburgh and its confluence with the [[Allegheny River]] to form the [[Ohio River]].  The river is navigable its entire length via a series of locks and dams.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe [[Unami language|Unami]] word ''Monongahela'' means \"falling banks\", in reference to the geological instability of the river's banks. [[Moravian Church|Moravian]] missionary [[David Zeisberger]] (1721\u20131808) gave this account of the naming: \"In the [[Lenape language|Indian tongue]] the name of this river was ''Mechmenawungihilla'' (alternatively spelled ''Menawngihella''), which signifies a high bank, which is ever washed out and therefore collapses.\"<ref>Zeisberger, David, ''David Zeisberger's History of the Northern American Indians in 18th Century Ohio, New York and Pennsylvania'', pg 43; Wennawoods Publishing, 1999, {{ISBN|1-889037-17-6}}</ref>\n\nThe Lenape Language Project renders the word as ''M\u00ebnaonkih\u00ebla'' (pronounced {{IPA-alg|m\u0259nao\u014b\u0261ih\u0259la|}}), translated \"where banks cave in or erode\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4599 |title=Lenape Talking Dictionary |accessdate=2010-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728081718/http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4599 |archive-date=2011-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> from the verbs ''m\u00ebnaonkih\u00eble'' \"the dirt caves off\" (such as the bank of a river or creek, or in a landslide)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4600 |title=Lenape Talking Dictionary |accessdate=2010-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728081520/http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4600 |archive-date=2011-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and ''m\u00ebnaonke'' (pronounced {{IPA-alg|m\u0259nao\u014b\u0261e|}}), \"it has a loose bank\" (where one might fall in).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4598 |title=Lenape Talking Dictionary |accessdate=2010-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728081526/http://www.talk-lenape.org/detail.php?id=4598 |archive-date=2011-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Monongalia County, West Virginia|Monongalia County]] and the town of [[Monongah, West Virginia|Monongah]], both in West Virginia, are named for the river, as is the city of [[Monongahela, Pennsylvania|Monongahela]] in Pennsylvania. (The name \"Monongalia\" is either a Latinized adaptation of \"Monongahela\" or simply a variant spelling.)\n\n===Variant names===\nThe USGS name for the river is the Monongahela River; there have been numerous alternate names, alternate spellings and misspellings in historical texts.{{efn|including Malangueul\u00e9,<ref>John Gilmary Shea. ''Relations diverses sur la bataille du Malangueul\u00e9 : gagn\u00e9 le 9 juillet, 1755, par les Fran\u00e7ois sous M. de Beaujeu, commandant du fort du Quesne sur les Anglois sous M. Braddock, g\u00e9n\u00e9ral en chef des troupes angloises''. Nouvelle York : De la Presse Cramoisy, 1860. {{OCLC|15760312}}.</ref> Me-nan-gi-hil-li, Meh-non-au-au-ge-hel-al, Mehmannaunringgehlau, Mehmannauwinggehla, Mo-hon-ga-ly, Mo-hon-galy, Mo-hon-gey-e-la, Mo-hong-gey-e-la, Mohungahala, Mohunghala, Monaung, Monaungahela, Monna, Monnyahela, Monona, Mononga, Monongahalia, Monongahaly, Monongaheley, Monongahelia, Monongalia, Monongalo, Mononguhela, Mononyahela, Muddy River <ref name=GNIS/>}}\n\n==Geography==\nThe Monongahela is formed by the confluence of the [[West Fork River]] and its \"east fork\"\u2014the [[Tygart Valley River]]\u2014at [[Fairmont, West Virginia|Fairmont]] in north central West Virginia. From there it flows northeasterly to cross the Pennsylvania border just west of north [[Cheat Lake]] on its [[Cheat River]] tributary. Then it flows northerly across southwestern Pennsylvania, taking a bit of a detour northeast 10 miles south of Pittsburgh to approach Pittsburgh from the southeast and its confluence with the [[Allegheny River]] to form the [[Forks of the Ohio]] at \"The Point\" of [[Point State Park]] in [[Downtown Pittsburgh]].\n\n==Geology==\nPrior to early Pleistocene regional glaciation, more than 780,000 years ago, the ancestral Monongahela River (a.k.a. the Pittsburgh River) flowed northward from present-day north-central West Virginia, across western [[Pennsylvania]] and northwestern Ohio, and into the [[Saint Lawrence River]] watershed. One (or more) extensive ice sheet advance dammed the old north-flowing drainage and created a vast lake\u2014known as [[Lake Monongahela]]\u2014stretching from an unknown point north of present-day [[Beaver, Pennsylvania]] for ~{{convert|200|mi|km}} south to [[Weston, West Virginia]]. A river-lake with many narrow bays, its maximum water surface rose to {{convert|1100|ft|m}} above sea level. Over {{convert|200|ft|m}} deep in places, its southwestward overflow gradually incised old drainage divides and contributed to the geological development of the present-day upper [[Ohio River Valley]].<ref name=\"Garton2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Garton |first1=E. Ray |title=Fauna of the Ice Age |journal=Wonderful West Virginia |date=January 2012 |pages=10-13 |url=http://www.wvdnr.gov/wwvmagazine/Archive/Batch2012/2012%20-%2001%20January.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Jacobson1988\">{{cite journal |last1=Jacobson |first1=Robert B. |last2=Elston |first2=Doland P. |last3=Heaton |first3=John R. |title=Stratigraphy and Magnetic Polarity of the High Terrace Remnants in the Upper Ohio and Monongahela Rivers in West Virginia, Pennsylvania, and Ohio |journal=Quaternary Research |date=May 1988 |volume=29 |issue=3 |pages=216-232 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/0033-5894(88)90031-2}}</ref>\n\n==Hydrography==\nVia the Ohio River, the river is part of the Mississippi watershed which drains to the Gulf of Mexico on the Atlantic Ocean.\n\nThe river's length is 130 miles, its drainage basin is 7,340sq.mi. and the average 30-year discharge at Elizabeth, Pennsylvania, is 9109cfs. It falls 3,831&nbsp;ft. in elevation from its forks to its mouth on the Ohio River.  The mean depth is about 20&nbsp;ft.\n\nIn southwestern Pennsylvania, the Monongahela is met by two major [[tributary|tributaries]]: the [[Cheat River]], which joins at [[Point Marion, Pennsylvania|Point Marion]], and the [[Youghiogheny River]], which joins at [[McKeesport, Pennsylvania|McKeesport]].\n\nMajor tributaries include: [[Becks Run]], [[Big Sandy Creek (Cheat River tributary)|Big Sandy Creek]], [[Buffalo Creek (Monongahela River tributary)|Buffalo Creek]], [[Cheat River]], [[Crooked Run (Monongahela River tributary)|Crooked Run]], [[Deckers Creek]], [[Dunkard Creek]], [[Lick Run (Peters Creek tributary)|Lick Run]], [[Middle Fork River]], [[Paw Paw Creek]], [[Peters Creek (Pennsylvania)|Peters Creek]], [[Streets Run]], [[Turtle Creek (Monongahela River tributary)|Turtle Creek]], [[Tygart Valley River]], [[West Fork River]], [[Youghiogheny River]].\n\n===Locks and dams===\n{{see also|List of dams and reservoirs in Pennsylvania}}\nThe river is navigable its entire length with a series of locks and dams that maintain a minimum depth of {{convert|9|ft|m|1}} to accommodate coal-laden barges. All dams are operated by the Pittsburgh District Army Corps of Engineers. In 2006, the navigation system, operated by the [[U.S. Army Corps of Engineers]], had nine dam-locks along {{convert|128.7|mi|km|1}} of waterway.<ref>{{cite web | title = Navigation | publisher = U.S. Army Corps of Engineers | year = 2006 | url = http://www.lrp.usace.army.mil/nav/nav.htm | accessdate = 2007-11-27 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071125094517/http://www.lrp.usace.army.mil/nav/nav.htm | archivedate = 2007-11-25 }}</ref> The locks overcame a change in elevation of about {{convert|147|ft|m|1}}.<ref name=shank />\n*[[Braddock Locks & Dam]] \t\n*[[Elizabeth Locks & Dam|Locks & Dam 3]]\n*[[Charleroi Locks & Dam|Locks & Dam 4]] \n*[[Maxwell Lock & Dam]] \t\n*[[Grays Landing Lock & Dam]] \n*[[Point Marion Lock and Dam]] \n*[[Morgantown Lock and Dam]] \t \n*[[Hildebrand Lock and Dam]] \t \n*[[Opekiska Lock and Dam]]\n\n==Ecology==\nAccording to the EPA's Toxics Release Inventory for 2010, the Monongahela ranked as the 17th most polluted river in the nation.<ref name=\"Hopey2012\">{{cite news |last1=Hopey |first1=Don |title=Region's rivers are some of nation's most polluted |url=https://www.post-gazette.com/news/nation/2012/03/23/Region-s-rivers-are-some-of-nation-s-most-polluted/stories/201203230179 |work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |date=2012-03-23}}</ref> The primary polluters were Pennsylvania iron and steel mills.\n\n==Recreation==\nThe upper drainage area of the river basin is renowned for its water sports/hobbies of [[whitewater kayaking]] (and in some cases [[whitewater rafting]]) opportunities. The land here is of a very rugged plateau type which allows streams to gather sufficient water volume before they fall off the plateau and create challenging rapids. Some of the best known specific stream locations for this include:\n*[[Youghiogheny River]] at [[Ohiopyle, Pennsylvania]]<ref>{{cite web|author=BradR |url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/1687/ |title=6. Lower, Youghiogheny Pennsylvania, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n*Youghiogheny River at [[Friendsville, Maryland]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/753/ |title=3. Upper, Youghiogheny Maryland, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n*[[Cheat River]] at [[Albright, West Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2346/ |title=1. (Narrows) Below Rowlesburg to above Albright Power Dam, Cheat West Virginia, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2347/ |title=2. (Canyon) Albright to Jenkinsburg Bridge, Cheat West Virginia, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n*[[Tygart River]] at [[Belington, West Virginia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2451/ |title=4. Belington to Buckhannon River, Tygart Valley West Virginia, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2452/ |title=5. Above Arden to Big Cove Run, Tygart Valley West Virginia, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanwhitewater.org/content/River/detail/id/2453/ |title=6. Valley Falls to Hammond, Tygart Valley West Virginia, US |publisher=American Whitewater |date= |accessdate=2018-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===18th and 19th centuries===\nThe Monongahela River valley was the site of a famous battle that was one of the first in the [[French and Indian War]]\u2014the [[Braddock Expedition]] (May\u2013July 1755). It resulted in a sharp defeat for two thousand [[British Empire|British]] and [[Thirteen Colonies|Colonial]] forces against those of the [[France|French]] and their [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] allies.\n\nIn 1817, the Pennsylvania legislature authorized the Monongahela Navigation Company to build 16 dams with bypass [[lock (water transport)|locks]] to create a river transportation system between Pittsburgh and the area that would later become West Virginia.<ref>[http://digital.library.pitt.edu/cgi-bin/f/findaid/findaid-idx?c=ascead&cc=ascead&rgn=main&view=text&didno=US-PPiU-dar193741 Monongahela Navigation Company Copybook], 1840-1897, DAR.1937.41, [[The Darlington Collection]], Special Collections Department, University of Pittsburgh</ref> Originally planned to run as far south as the Cheat River, the system was extended to Fairmont, and [[bituminous coal]] from West Virginia was the chief product transported downstream. After a [[Pennsylvania Canal Tunnel|canal tunnel through Grant's Hill]] in Pittsburgh was completed in 1832, boats could travel between the Monongahela River and the Western Division Canal of Pennsylvania's principal east-west canal and railroad system, the [[Main Line of Public Works]]. In 1897, the federal government took possession of the Monongahela Navigation through [[eminent domain|condemnation]] proceedings. Later, the dam-lock combinations were increased in size and reduced in number.<ref name=shank>{{cite book | last = Shank | first = William H. | title = The Amazing Pennsylvania Canals, 150th Anniversary Edition | publisher = American Canal and Transportation Center | year = 1986 | page = 76 | location = York, Pennsylvania | isbn=0-933788-37-1}}</ref>\n\nBriefly linked to the Monongahela Navigation was the Youghiogheny Navigation, a slack water system of {{convert|18.5|mi|km|1}} between McKeesport and [[West Newton, Pennsylvania|West Newton]]. It had two dam-locks overcoming a change in elevation of about {{convert|27|ft|m|}}. Opening in 1850, it was destroyed by a flood in 1865.<ref name=shank />\n\nDuring the 19th century, the Monongahela was heavily used by [[industry]], and several [[U.S. Steel]] plants, including the [[Homestead, Pennsylvania|Homestead]] Works, site of the [[Homestead Strike]] of 1892, were built along its banks. Following the killing of several workers in the course of the strike, anarchist [[Emma Goldman]] wrote: \"Words had lost their meaning in the face of the innocent blood spilled on the banks of the Monongahela.\"\n\n===20th century===\nThree ships in the [[United States Navy]] have been named [[USS Monongahela|''Monongahela'']] after the river.\nIn October 1930, severe drought caused the river flow to drop below 10cfs, and in some places, it was possible to walk across the river bottom.{{Citation needed|reason=not clear where this info comes from|date=April 2019}}\n\nThe river was the site of a [[List of accidents and incidents involving military aircraft (1955\u20131959)#1956|famous airplane crash]] that has become the subject of numerous [[urban legend]]s and [[conspiracy theories]]. Early in the morning of January 31, 1956, a [[B-25]] bomber en route from [[Nellis Air Force Base]] in [[Nevada]] to [[Olmsted Air Force Base]] in Pennsylvania crashed into the river near the [[Glenwood Bridge]] in [[Homestead, Pennsylvania]]. All six crewmen survived the crash, but two later succumbed to [[hypothermia|exposure]] and drowned. Despite the relative shallowness of the water, the aircraft was never recovered.<ref>\n{{cite web | title = The Pittsburgh B-25 Ghost Bomber Mystery (1956) |date= 2017-05-15\n| url = http://pittsburgh.about.com/od/transportation/a/b25_bomber.htm# |first=Albrecht|last= Powell|publisher=About.com| accessdate = 2020-01-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Searchers say 'Ghost Bomber' can be found in the Mon |first=Torsten |last= Ove| date = 1999-04-04 | url = http://old.post-gazette.com/regionstate/19990404bomber4.asp | accessdate = 2016-02-13  }}</ref> The ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'' published a graphical representation of the flight path and flight details in 1999.<ref>{{cite web \n| title = PG Graphic: One of the Mysteries of Pittsburgh: The B-25 in the Mon |first=James|last=Hilston | work= Pittsburgh Post-Gazette |url = http://old.post-gazette.com/regionstate/19990404plane9.asp | date = 1999-04-04  }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web | title = Let's learn from the past: B-25 'Ghost Bomber' |work= Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | url = http://www.post-gazette.com/life/my-generation/2016/01/07/Let-s-learn-from-the-past-B-25-Ghost-Bomber.html# | date = 2016-01-07 | first=Brady|last=Smith}}\n</ref> As of October 2018, the bomber has not been found.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nImage:Monongahela River Pittsburgh.jpg|The [[South Tenth Street Bridge]] over the Monongahela River in [[Pittsburgh]] in 2005\nImage:Monongahela River Fairmont.jpg|The Monongahela River in [[Fairmont, West Virginia]], in 2006\nImage:Monongahela River Scene Pittsburgh PA 1857.jpg|Monongahela River Scene, 1857<ref>''Ballou's Pictorial'', issue of 21 Feb 1857</ref>\nImage:Opekiska Lock and Dam Monongahela.jpg|[[Opekiska Lock and Dam]] on the Monongahela River near [[Fairmont, West Virginia]], at [[river mile]] 115 ({{cvt|115|mi|disp=out}})\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of crossings of the Monongahela River]]\n*[[List of rivers of Pennsylvania]]\n*[[List of rivers of West Virginia]]\n*[[Geography of Pennsylvania]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*[[Richard Pike Bissell|Bissell, Richard]] (1952), ''The Monongahela'', [[Rinehart & Co.]]\n*Callahan, James Morton and Bernard Lee Butcher (1912), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=FGAMAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Genealogical and Personal History of the Upper Monongahela Valley, West Virginia]'', [[New York City|New York]]: Lewis Historical Publishing Company.\n*[[Earl Lemley Core|Core, Earl L.]] (1984), \"The Monongalia River,\" in: Bartlett, Richard A. (ed), ''Rolling Rivers: An Encyclopedia of America's Rivers.'' New York: McGraw-Hill. {{ISBN|0-07-003910-0}}. pp 149\u201352.\n*Core, Earl L. (1974\u201384), ''The Monongalia Story: A Bicentennial History'', [[Parsons, West Virginia|Parsons, W.Va.]]: [[McClain Printing Co.]], 5 volumes; an extensive, well-documented natural & human history of the Monongahela River basin.\n**Volume I: ''Prelude'' (1974)\n**Volume II: ''The Pioneers'' (1976)\n**Volume III: ''Discord'' (1979)\n**Volume IV: ''Industrialization'' (1984)\n**Volume V: